Including plugin servlet by calling <jsp:include> doesn't work.

See also https://studio.atlassian.com/browse/PLUG-233

To determine which plugin servlet to execute fisheye uses url from reqest.getPathInfo(). That doesn't work for servlets called from <jsp:include> because pathInfo in this case will contain path of original request. It should use request.getAttribute("javax.servlet.include.path_info") instead.             

It looks like fix should be in FisheyeServletModuleContainerServlet.java
Line 48 
{code}
  final DelegatingPluginServlet servlet = getServletModuleManager().getServlet(request.getPathInfo(), servletConfig);
{code}

should be changed to:
{code}
String pathInfo = (String) request.getAttribute("javax.servlet.include.path_info");
if (pathInfo==null)
{
  pathInfo = request.getPathInfo();
}
final DelegatingPluginServlet servlet = getServletModuleManager().getServlet(pathInfo, servletConfig);
{code}

Created from [FSH-1378|https://support.atlassian.com/browse/FSH-1378]. 

{quote}
If I create a repository with branch //depot/dir1/dir2/dir3 with no includes/excludes specified I get exactly what I expect. I would also expect to get exactly the same results if I specified the same branch using a different root and using include directories. ie, branch //depot and include directory dir1/dir2/dir3. However, this second configuration results in the entire depot being scanned which eventually dies because of maxScanRows being exceeded.
{quote}

As [pointed out by Eric|https://extranet.atlassian.com/crucible/cru/CR-FE-530#c4450] the following ServerSocket accept code allows means {{handleClient}} ought to be reentrant, but there's no explicit synchronisation coded. 

{code}
    private void runServer() {
        Logs.APP_LOG.info("listening on " + mBind);
        try {
            while (!mStopping) {
                final Socket socket = mSvr.accept();
                Logs.APP_LOG.debug("Socket timeout is " + socket.getSoTimeout());
                try {
                    Thread commandThread = new Thread(new Runnable() {
                        public void run() {
                            handleClient(socket);
                        }
                    });
                    commandThread.start();
                } catch (RuntimeException e) {
                    Logs.APP_LOG.error("unexpected exception", e);
                } catch (Error e) {
                    Logs.APP_LOG.error("unexpected error", e);
                }
            }
        } catch (IOException e) {
            if (!mStopping) {
                Logs.APP_LOG.warn("shutdown socket disabled", e);
            }
        }
    }
{code}

The underlying repository operations are synchronised, but it's possible to get into race conditions (e.g. multple calls to reindex)
